    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper argues that a class of highly structured dynamical systems on 3-dimensional spaces\u2014called Bott-integrable contact forms\u2014can nonetheless exhibit arbitrarily extreme geometry, contrary to the intuition that their built-in symmetry should impose limits. The review board found the paper's strategy promising and well-grounded in reliable prior work. The main caveat is that the central new technical piece\u2014equipping a key building block called the ABHS plug with the required symmetry structure\u2014is sketched by appeal to visual symmetry and an external reference rather than proved in full. The paper is likely correct but requires closer scrutiny of one key step before the result can be considered fully established.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper claims that for any Bott-integrable contact structure on a closed 3-manifold, Bott-integrable contact forms with arbitrarily large systolic ratio exist (Theorem 1). The proof architecture\u2014linearizing Lutz forms via piecewise-linear approximation and inserting ABHS small-volume plugs\u2014is coherent and relies on published results from Inventiones Math. and Ann. Sc. Norm. Super. Pisa. The sole new technical contribution is Addendum 4, which aims to construct a \u03c6-invariant Morse\u2013Bott function on the ABHS plug; all three reviewers independently identified across two cycles that the \u03c6-invariance is described informally and not explicitly verified. Secondary moderate gaps are: the contact condition f\u00b7g\u2032\u2212g\u00b7f\u2032>0 under convex interpolation in Proposition 2 is asserted without a quantitative C\u00b9-margin argument; a Gray-stability step needed to recover the exact contact structure \u03be from the constructed homotopy is not stated; and the global Morse\u2013Bott seam matching across plug boundaries is asserted rather than constructed."
    }
